API parity — what actually changes.

Once you have internalized the mental model, the code surface turns out to be small. Batch and streaming use the same dataframe transformations — filter, select, group-by, join, agg, and the window functions. Only the input and output boundary is different. In fact, exactly five things change.

First, you write spark dot read-stream, instead of spark dot read — and you must provide an explicit schema, because Spark cannot infer one from an unbounded source.

Second, you write dataframe dot write-stream, instead of dataframe dot write.

Third, you set an output-mode — which controls which rows to emit per micro-batch.

Fourth, you set the option checkpoint-location — which is where Spark persists the offsets, the state, and the write-ahead log.

And fifth, start returns a streaming-query handle — whereas write, in batch, simply returned none.

Everything in between the read and the write is identical dataframe code. That is the API parity. And it is precisely why the same logic can power both a historical backfill and live processing, with only minimal change.
